    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-06-03T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-06-03T09:00:00-05:00" n="357"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d357">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 341.622a/145</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-06-03T16:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 3, 1916, 4 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 4, 4.05 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3951. In conversation with <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von Jagow</persName>
                    yesterday he referred to fact that copies of American notes to England such as
                        <hi rend="italic">China</hi> steamer case, taking of mails, etc.,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d357fn2">See the sections dealing with “The Removal by Belligerent
                        Naval Authorties of Enemy Subjects and Military Reservists from American
                        Ships on the High Seas,” <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_630"
                            >p. 630</ref>, and “Interference with the Mails by Belligerent
                        Governments,” <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_591">p.
                            591</ref>.</note> were not published, while American notes to Germany
                    were invariably published, often before received. He said that he thought it
                    would do much good if these notes were published here.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
